Learner Map Demo📍🗺

This is a short demo to show you how easy it can be to create impressive figures and documents with R and Rmarkdown. I’ll put the code into the chat so that you can create the map too!

Do this to start

  • Go to Google maps, find your area, right-click and copy your coordinates (latitude, longitude).

  • Paste your coordinates into this form here: https://forms.gle/1XoxfkhGLxqEHik9A

  • Open a new R script (top left button in Rstudio)

  • Paste in code.

  • Install packages

# install.packages(c('tidyverse', 'leaflet', 'googlesheets4'))
# load packages
library(tidyverse)
library(googlesheets4)
library(leaflet)

Google API

Google offers an Application Programming Interface (API) to work with files stored in the cloud through code.

The data you entered into the form are collected into a spreadsheet that anyone can read from.

(You’ll need a google account to their API. googlesheets4 will prompt you to set up an access token for your account, then Google will ask you to confirm that you want to allow the tidyverse API to access your files. Make sure to check the box that allows the Tidyverse API to have it’s way with your files, or else your requests will be denied.

coords <-
  # read data from this url
  "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1EpByX-P6ou74xqcTF4gX388g-zbMEHPyHsBZADyMhsU/edit?usp=sharing" |> 
  googlesheets4::read_sheet() |> 
  filter(!is.na(Timestamp))

# preview data

Now that our data is loaded, let’s create some html-formatted text with details to show as popups for each marker.

# mutate() creates a new column that we've called 'popup'
# str_glue() inserts our data variables into a text template,
# variables are referenced by name in code expressions wrapped with {}
coords <- coords |>
  mutate(popup = str_glue(
    'Responded at <b>{Timestamp}</b><br>
     Lat ~ <b>{round(latitude, 2)}</b><br>
     Lng ~ <b>{round(longitude, 2)}</b>') |> 
      as.character()
    )

# check the new column we created
coords |> head()

Leaflet

We’ll use the Leaflet package to build our map in layers: canvas -> background -> data markers.

# blank map
leaflet::leaflet() |>
  # add the base layer style
  leaflet::addProviderTiles(
    providers$CartoDB,
    options = providerTileOptions(noWrap = TRUE)
  ) |>
  # add markers based on survey data
  leaflet::addMarkers(
    data = coords,
    lng = ~longitude,
    lat = ~latitude,
    label = ~str_glue('{latitude}, {longitude}'),
    popup = ~popup
    )
